  "prompt": "How are the types of nerve cell structured?",
  "response": "Nerve cells, or neurons, have a complex structure that allows them to transmit electrical and chemical signals throughout the nervous system. Here's a breakdown of their typical structure:\n\n1. Cell Body (Soma)\n- Contains the nucleus\n- Manages cell metabolism\n- Synthesizes proteins and cellular components\n\n2. Dendrites\n- Branch-like projections\n- Receive signals from other neurons\n- Conduct electrical signals toward the cell body\n- Can have multiple dendrites per neuron\n\n3. Axon\n- Long, thin projection\n- Transmits electrical signals away from the cell body\n- Usually covered in myelin sheath for faster signal transmission\n- Ends in terminal branches with synaptic terminals\n\n4. Synaptic Terminals\n- Located at axon ends\n- Release neurotransmitters\n- Connect with other neurons' dendrites or target cells\n\n5. Types of Neurons\n- Sensory neurons: Transmit sensory information\n- Motor neurons: Control muscle movements\n- Interneurons: Connect different neurons within the nervous system\n\nEach type of neuron has a slightly different structure tailored to its specific function, but these basic components are generally consistent across nerve cell types.",
